ce:section.ce:para:
Diniconazole, [1-(2,4-Dichlorophenyl)-4,4-dimethyl-2-(1H-1,2,4-triazol-1-yl)pent-1-en-3-ol], with condensed chemical formula of C16H17Cl2N3O and molecular weight of 326.2 g mol−1 is one of the members of triazole fungicides (Fig. 1
                     ), that is widely utilized in controlling a wide variety of diseases like scab, septoria, brown rust, powdery mildew and Rynchosporium [1,2]. In spite of its wide usage, its residue causes environmental and health problems. The maximum residue limit (MRL) for diniconazole has been defined as 0.01 mg kg−1 
                     [3]. There are many techniques to determine diniconazole residues in diverse kinds of samples such as Gas chromatography (GC), High Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC) [2], gas chromatography–mass spectrometry (GC–MS) [4,5], and high-performance liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry (HPLC-MS) [6], and time-resolved fluoroimmunoassay [7]. But, it is still of utmost importance to find rapid and cost-effective methods for the assay of pesticide residues. Chemiluminescence (CL) is a powerful tool in the environmental investigation because of its extensive dynamic range, high sensitivity, low detection limit, and its cost-effectiveness [8].
